Location:
Every neighborhood in San Francisco has its own unique characteristics that set it apart from the rest of the city, while at the same time exuding an undertone that clearly denotes its San Francisco residency. The Inner Sunset is a perfect example, bubbling with diversity with a beat in-line with big city living.

Boasted as one of the most beloved neighborhoods by San Franciscans, the Inner Sunset has a laid-back, small-town feel with a funky edge that keeps the neighborhood fresh. Home to a widely diverse mix of people, the local businesses have no problem keeping up with the latest in cuisine and retail selections.

Its northern edge heads right into Golden Gate Park, a nicety that can quickly clog up any parking privileges privy to residential districts, particularly during large events and weekends. The Inner Sunset is also home to UCSF that serves as both a school and medical facility, which keeps the neighborhood buzzing with grad students and visitors who flock to the medical facility for the most innovative and advanced medical services in the country.

A walk down any street in the neighborhood will make it clear that the residents all know one another, nodding and chatting as they gather at mom-and-pop diners, drug stores, shoe repair shops, and small grocers on their daily outings.

The Inner Sunset may be one of the foggiest districts in all of San Francisco, but it doesn t seem to deter the locals from gathering in this warm-hearted and trendy borough.

The North Panhandle neighborhood has quickly become a household name in San Francisco, although it is better known as NoPa.

NoPa s borders surround mostly residential properties, but its key location is convenient to some of the city s most popular destination restaurants and a growing number of storefronts. The eastern border runs along Divisadero Street, which is fast-paced with foot-traffic energy, boutique and vintage shops, epicurean desirables, and organic grocers.

Residents who live in this neighborhood enjoy the amenity of not having to own an automobile to get around in the district and out to every corner of the city. Some longtime residents will also admit that they find little reason to leave the area, as all of the city s amenities are within reach.

The neighborhood s westernmost border opens right up into Golden Gate Park providing endless opportunities for outdoor recreation and activities. Across the Panhandle, the long southern border along Fell Street provides a direct route to the freeway for residents that work outside the city or need a quick getaway. Other neighboring districts offer proximity to the University of San Francisco as well as the main facility for Kaiser Permanente.

With a growing number of destination restaurants and storefronts igniting its soaring popularity, becoming a resident of the North Panhandle would be an honor in the eyes of many San Franciscans.

This southwestern neighborhood was once an expanse of sand dunes. But once its potential was recognized, the Inner Parkside along with its neighbors became a desirable lot of land filled with a diverse community and San Francisco charm.

Inner Parkside is a long residential stretch with an optimal city location. The neighborhood enjoys close proximity to San Francisco favorites like Stern Grove, Golden Gate Park and the Pacific Ocean. Although it is only a fraction of the size of its neighbor Parkside, it packs a punch with its unique charm and distinct character.

This family-centric neighborhood is filled with modest homes and small storefronts that give it a small-town feel. Neat stucco homes in the architectural style of the 1920s to 1940s line the streets, resembling houses in nearby neighborhoods.

One of its most energetic nearby neighborhoods is West Portal, which offers residents an abundance of boutique shopping and a variety of dining and entertainment options, including a movie theater, all accessible by foot.

Exempt from the tourist traffic that swarms to other San Francisco locales, the Inner Parkside has remained a preserved residential respite from big city chaos. Residents of this neighborhood are able to enjoy a suburban lifestyle, but are rewarded with the options of big city amenities at their will.

Location:

Diamond Heights is a neighborhood that contains the expansive outdoor space of Glen Canyon Park, with two residential pockets on the two hills at its northern and southeastern borders.

A late bloomer in terms of San Francisco neighborhood development, Diamond Heights did not form until the 1960s as a response to the post-war housing demands that ignited a development frenzy. The community was the very first project for the San Francisco Planning and Urban Research Association whose main goal was to redevelop areas using their inherent characteristics, such as the two hills that make up most of Diamond Heights today. The homes that were built here in the 1960s are still largely under ownership by their original titleholders, including some of the multi-unit rental properties.

The area has one main commercial center for residents, located on Diamond Heights Boulevard, which caters to most of the resident s essential needs. And thanks to its bordering districts, the residents of Diamond Heights can enjoy their small suburb and amazing views, and easily take a public bus or short drive to enjoy the trendier urban amenities of Noe Valley or Glen Park.

The biggest attraction in Diamond Heights is Glen Canyon Park, boasting 63 acres of officially sanctioned undeveloped natural area that represents the true terrain of the region as it was before the massive redevelopment.

This tucked-away neighborhood surrounded by nature is ideal for serene residential living equipped with stunning views in a central location only minutes away from city life.

I have lived in this apartment for the past 3 years. Prior to that it was a short-term rental for 2 years. My mother has lived in the 2-bedroom unit on the 3rd floor for the past 14 years. Her lease includes a small in-law unit on the ground floor. We are both moving out, so that unit will be available as well soon. The 3rd floor tenant gets half of the garage, the smaller laundry machine and access to the back yard.

Both units have separate meters, so tenants pay all the utilities. I have been paying utilities for the whole building the past few years. The owner installed solar panels 2 years ago, but it didn't make much of a dent in my PG&E bill, except in September and October. New electric stoves were installed. Electric heaters were installed in all bedrooms and living areas. The only items left to replace are the laundry machines. Those still run on gas. They may get replaced in the next few months, and then the gas will be shut off.

The building is very close to the corner of 23rd & Irving, a busy retail area known to locals as "Chinatown West". It's quite busy outside the building during the day, especially on Weekends. If you're sensitive to noise, this property may not a good fit. We frequently hear cars honking from Irving Street. The retail building around the corner has new HVAC mechanical equipment on the roof which is a bit noisy.

The homeless situation is not too bad in our neighborhood. Once in a while there are some crazies yelling on Irving Street and you'll see a few shady-looking people walking around, but overall, the neighborhood and our street is generally quite safe.

The building next door has been under construction since February. It has been very painful with all the noise, but the project is almost done. They are just putting on the final touches, and the owner's adult kids will occupy the 2-unit property. The neighbor on the other side is a couple with two young kids.

LOCATION
NoPa s borders surround mostly residential properties, but its key location is convenient to some of the city s most popular destination restaurants and a growing number of storefronts. The eastern border runs along Divisadero Street, which is fast-paced with foot-traffic energy, boutique and vintage shops, epicurean desirables, and organic grocers.

Residents who live in this neighborhood enjoy the amenity of not having to own an automobile to get around in the district and out to every corner of the city. Some longtime residents will also admit that they find little reason to leave the area, as all of the city s amenities are within reach.

The neighborhood s westernmost border opens right up into Golden Gate Park providing endless opportunities for outdoor recreation and activities. Across the Panhandle, the long southern border along Fell Street provides a direct route to the freeway for residents that work outside the city or need a quick getaway. Other neighboring districts offer proximity to the University of San Francisco as well as the main facility for Kaiser Permanente.

With a growing number of destination restaurants and storefronts igniting its soaring popularity, becoming a resident of the North Panhandle would be an honor in the eyes of many San Franciscans.
